{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01UcLQbeRpxcMpLUugEk7Cet","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I have a clear picture. The implementation already exists in `tui.go`. I need to add unit tests that explicitly cover all 4 acceptance criteria:\n\n1. AC1: \"After successful installation, a prompt asks the user if they want to open the store URL.\"\n   - View test: `phaseOpenBrowser` view contains the store URL and prompt text (\"Open ... in your browser?\")\n\n2. AC2: \"Pressing `y` opens the URL in the system default browser (macOS, Linux, Windows).\"\n   - Test: pressing `y` at `phaseOpenBrowser` sets `browserOpened = true` and transitions to `phaseInstallDone`\n   - We can't easily test the actual browser opening, but we can verify `browserOpened == true`\n\n3. AC3: \"Pressing `n` or `q` exits without opening the browser.\"\n   - Test: pressing `n` at `phaseOpenBrowser` transitions to `phaseInstallDone` with `browserOpened == false`\n   - Test: pressing `q` at `phaseOpenBrowser` calls `tea.Quit` (the global q handler) with `browserOpened == false`\n\n4. AC4: \"The store URL matches the configured base URL for the selected environment.\"\n   - Test: the URL shown in `phaseOpenBrowser` matches the base URL from the detector for the selected environment and project name\n\nNow I'm realizing that when `q` is pressed during the browser phase, the global key handler at the top of `Update()` catches it first and immediately quits the app, so `browserOpened` stays false without us needing to explicitly set it. This naturally satisfies the requirement. Let me add these test cases to `tui_test.go`.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":2170,"cache_read_input_tokens":47651,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":2170},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","infere